Code Page 936 Encoding and Decoding

Published August 11, 2024
By Samuel Yang

Code Page 936 is an extended ASCII character encoding commonly used in Microsoft Windows to represent Simplified Chinese characters. It is also known as the Windows-936 or GBK (Guobiao Kuozhan) encoding. GBK is an extension of the earlier GB 2312 standard, which was used for encoding Simplified Chinese in China.

Code Page 936 (CP936) uses different byte sequences to represent different types of characters:

  • Single-Byte Characters
    The valid lead byte ranges for single-byte sequences are as follows:
    • 0x00-0x80
  • Two-Byte Characters
    The valid lead byte ranges for double-byte sequences are as follows:
    • 0xA1-0xF7
    • 0x81-0xFE


    The valid trail byte ranges for double-byte sequences are as follows:
    • 0xA1-0xFE
    • 0x40-0xFE

Code Page 936 (CP936) includes characters from:

  • ASCII occupy the range 0x00-0x80
  • GB 2312 (Simplified Chinese Characters) occupy the range 0xA1A1-0xFEFE. This is the main component of CP936 and includes approximately 7,000 characters, covering Simplified Chinese hanzi (Chinese characters), punctuation marks, and other symbols.
  • GBK (Guobiao Kuozhan) occupy the ranges 0x8140-0xFEFE. GBK is an extension of GB 2312 and includes a much larger set of characters. GBK adds over 13,000 characters to the original 7,000 provided by GB 2312, covering more hanzi (Chinese characters), traditional characters, and additional symbols

The Private Use Area (PUA) is designated for characters that are not part of the standard character sets defined by GB 2312 or other official standards. This area allows users and organizations to define their own characters for specialized or proprietary purposes.

The Private Use Area in CP936 is located within the following ranges:

  • Lead Byte Ranges: 0x80-0xFE
  • Trail Byte Ranges: 0x40-0xFE
